**GOVERNING THE PLANETARY-SCALE ORGANISM:

A PUBLIC-PRIVATE SYNTHETIC INFRASTRUCTURE FRAMEWORK FOR 21ST CENTURY SOCIO-TECHNICAL SYSTEMS**

Author : ouadi Maakoul & USA LLM

ABSTRACT

This dissertation develops a novel governance framework for planetary-scale socio-technical systems, moving beyond critiques of corporate power or utopian solutionism. Through an embedded case study of Tesla's integrated ecosystem—encompassing autonomous mobility (vehicles), distributed intelligence (sensors), embodied AI (Optimus robots), and renewable energy infrastructure (SolarCity)—it theorizes the emergence of a Public-Private Synthetic Infrastructure (PPSI).

The research addresses a fundamental tension in 21st century technological development: how to harness the capabilities of globally integrated, intelligent systems for public benefit while preserving democratic sovereignty, individual privacy, and human agency. The proposed framework resolves this through a Data-for-Infrastructure (D4I) governance model, wherein anonymized, aggregated intelligence from private systems informs public planning and maintenance without surveillance or corporate control of civic functions.

Methodologically, the dissertation employs a tripartite approach: (1) conceptual framework development grounded in socio-technical systems theory and polycentric governance; (2) embedded case analysis of Tesla's evolving ecosystem; and (3) normative institutional design for hybrid governance structures. The resulting framework introduces several original constructs: Robot-Compatible Urbanism for proactive city design; Privacy-Preserving Digital Twins as public utilities; and Labor Transmutation as an alternative to technological unemployment narratives.

The primary theoretical contribution is the reconceptualization of planetary-scale corporate platforms as potential civilizational learning infrastructures—systems that can enhance both physical infrastructure and human capability through symbiotic feedback loops. By positioning governance not as external regulation but as an integrated layer within the intelligence cycle, this research provides a normative template for managing 21st century intelligent systems, wherein technological capability and civic authority are synergistically aligned for continuous civilizational enhancement without compromising freedom.

Keywords: Socio-technical systems, Polycentric governance, Public-private partnerships, Autonomous systems, Urban intelligence, Infrastructure governance, AI ethics, Technological sovereignty, Distributed energy, Human-robot collaboration

