```

E.2 Algorithmic Impact Assessment Template

ASSESSMENT FRAMEWORK FOR NEW PPSI CAPABILITIES

```
SECTION A: SYSTEM CHARACTERIZATION
A1. Technical Description:
- Purpose and function
- Data inputs and sources
- Decision-making process
- Outputs and actions

A2. Deployment Context:
- Scale of deployment
- User populations affected
- Geographic scope
- Integration with existing systems

SECTION B: IMPACT ASSESSMENT  
B1. Beneficial Impacts:
- Efficiency improvements (quantified)
- Cost reductions (projected)
- Service enhancements
- Innovation enablement

B2. Potential Harms:
- Privacy risks (type and magnitude)
- Bias and discrimination risks
- Safety concerns
- Dependency creation

B3. Distributional Effects:
- Who benefits disproportionately?
- Who bears costs or risks?
- Geographic distribution
- Demographic differentials

SECTION C: MITIGATION STRATEGIES
C1. Technical Safeguards:
- Privacy protections
- Bias detection and correction
- Safety interlocks
- Transparency mechanisms

C2. Institutional Controls:
- Human oversight requirements
- Audit protocols
- Appeal processes
- Sunsetting provisions

C3. Community Protections:
- Opt-out mechanisms
- Redress procedures
- Community review processes
- Impact monitoring commitments

SECTION D: MONITORING AND EVALUATION
D1. Performance Metrics:
- Success criteria
- Harm indicators
- Equity measures
- Efficiency benchmarks

D2. Review Process:
- Evaluation frequency
- Stakeholder participation
- Transparency requirements
- Adaptation procedures

RISK CLASSIFICATION:
- Level 1 (Minimal): No significant impacts, proceed
- Level 2 (Limited): Minor impacts, proceed with monitoring
- Level 3 (Moderate): Significant impacts, require mitigations
- Level 4 (High): Major impacts, require extensive safeguards
- Level 5 (Severe): Unacceptable risks, do not proceed
```

APPENDIX F: CASE STUDY SIMULATIONS

F.1 Singapore Implementation Simulation

CONTEXT ANALYSIS

```
Strengths:
- Strong technical infrastructure (95% fiber coverage)
- Integrated government data systems
- High digital literacy (92% population)
- Robust regulatory frameworks
- Financial capacity for investment

Challenges:  
- High population density creating complexity
- Legacy systems integration
- Multicultural sensitivity requirements
- Geopolitical positioning considerations

IMPLEMENTATION APPROACH: MANAGED SERVICE PARTNERSHIP
Phase 1 (Months 1-12): Digital Twin Development
- Deploy vehicle sensors on public transport fleet (3000 vehicles)
- Establish secure municipal data environment
- Develop traffic optimization algorithms for CBD
- Implement privacy-preserving data sharing protocols

Phase 2 (Months 13-36): Integrated Systems Deployment
- Robot-compatible retrofitting of Marina Bay district
- Virtual Power Plant integration with HDB housing
- Workforce transition programs for transportation sector
- Real-time infrastructure monitoring city-wide

Phase 3 (Months 37-60): Ecosystem Maturation
- Autonomous last-mile delivery corridors
- Predictive maintenance for entire road network
- AI-assisted urban planning tools
- Export of Singapore-developed solutions

Key Performance Indicators:
- Traffic congestion reduction: Target 25%
- Energy efficiency improvement: Target 30%
- Workforce transition success: Target 90%
- Public satisfaction: Target 85%
```

