APPENDIX G: ETHICAL GUIDELINES AND ASSESSMENT TOOLS

G.1 Structural Privacy Assessment Tool

TECHNICAL AUDIT CHECKLIST

```
Category 1: Data Minimization
- [ ] Sensors collect only necessary features
- [ ] Raw data processed at edge when possible
- [ ] Aggregation before transmission where feasible
- [ ] Default collection settings minimize data

Category 2: Anonymization Robustness  
- [ ] k-anonymity ≥50 maintained in all releases
- [ ] Differential privacy with ε ≤1.0 implemented
- [ ] Re-identification risk <0.01% for all datasets
- [ ] Longitudinal privacy protected across time

Category 3: Access Controls
- [ ] Role-based access with minimum necessary privileges
- [ ] All access logged and regularly audited
- [ ] Automated alerts for suspicious access patterns
- [ ] Data deletion protocols automatically enforced

Category 4: Transparency
- [ ] Public documentation of data practices
- [ ] Clear privacy notices for affected individuals
- [ ] Regular transparency reports published
- [ ] Data use tracking publicly accessible

Category 5: Security
- [ ] Encryption in transit and at rest
- [ ] Regular security penetration testing
- [ ] Incident response plan tested annually
- [ ] Secure deletion of decommissioned devices

SCORING:
- ≥90%: Excellent privacy protection
- 75-89%: Good with minor improvements needed
- 60-74%: Fair, significant improvements needed
- <60%: Inadequate, major redesign required
```

G.2 Equity Impact Assessment Matrix

QUANTITATIVE IMPACT MEASUREMENT

```
Dimension 1: Access Distribution
- Geographic coverage by income quintile
- Service reliability across neighborhoods
- Affordability metrics by demographic group
- Digital access and literacy correlation

Dimension 2: Benefit Allocation  
- Cost savings distribution
- Time savings allocation
- Health and safety improvements
- Economic opportunity creation

Dimension 3: Risk Distribution
- Privacy risks by population segment
- Safety concerns across areas
- Dependency creation risks
- Displacement or disruption impacts

Dimension 4: Participation
- Decision-making involvement
- Feedback mechanism accessibility
- Redress process effectiveness
- Transparency and information access

EQUITY INDEX CALCULATION:
Access Equality Score = 1 - (Gini coefficient of access)
Benefit Distribution Score = % benefits to bottom 40%
Risk Equity Score = 1 - (Risk concentration index)
Participation Score = % population engaged in governance

Overall Equity Score = Weighted average (weights adjustable by context)
- Minimum acceptable: 0.7
- Good performance: 0.8-0.9
- Excellent: >0.9
```

G.3 Capability Ethics Assessment Framework

HUMAN DEVELOPMENT IMPACT MEASURES

```
Capability Category 1: Practical Reason
- Decision-making autonomy preserved/enhanced
- Understanding of system operations
- Ability to shape system evolution
- Critical reflection on technology use

Capability Category 2: Affiliation  
- Social connections maintained/strengthened
- Community participation opportunities
- Cultural practices supported
- Intergenerational knowledge transfer

Capability Category 3: Bodily Health
- Physical safety improved
- Health outcomes enhanced
- Environmental quality maintained
- Work-related risks reduced

Capability Category 4: Senses, Imagination, Thought
- Learning opportunities expanded
- Creative expression supported
- Cultural engagement enabled
- Intellectual development fostered

Capability Category 5: Emotions
- Dignity preserved/enhanced
- Meaningful work maintained
- Stress reduction achieved
- Psychological well-being supported

ASSESSMENT METHODOLOGY:
1. Baseline measurement before implementation
2. Annual longitudinal tracking
3. Mixed methods: surveys, interviews, observation
4. Participatory assessment with community
5. Comparative analysis across demographic groups

INTERVENTION THRESHOLDS:
- Negative impact on any core capability: Requires mitigation
- No improvement in majority of capabilities: Reevaluate approach
- Improvement in all capabilities: Successful implementation
- Significant enhancement in multiple capabilities: Exemplary outcome
```

These appendices provide the detailed technical specifications, legal frameworks, implementation tools, and assessment methodologies necessary to operationalize the Public-Private Synthetic Infrastructure framework developed in this dissertation. They bridge the gap between theoretical proposal and practical implementation, offering actionable resources for policymakers, municipal leaders, corporate partners, and communities embarking on the governance of planetary-scale socio-technical systems.
